{
"id":"mk19_a_id_s7",
"subspecialtyId":"id",
"title":"Nontuberculous Mycobacterial Infections",
"jsonContent":{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_a_id_s7",
"title":{
"__html":"Nontuberculous Mycobacterial Infections"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"54f9cc",
"children":[
"Nontuberculous Mycobacterial Infections"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_a_id_s7_0",
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"4e4fef",
"children":[
"Nontuberculous mycobacteria (NTM) comprise species other than ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium tuberculosis"
]
},
" complex and ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium leprae"
]
},
". NTM are divided into slow and rapid growers ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"span",
"attrs":{
"className":"text-nowrap"
},
"children":[
"(",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
{
"type":"table-link",
"target":"mk19_a_id_t23",
"wrapId":"1",
"children":[
"Table 23"
]
}
]
},
")"
]
},
". These organisms are found in water, soil, domestic and wild animals, milk, and food products. They can be colonizers, particularly in the airways of persons with chronic lung disease, and cause a spectrum of infections ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"span",
"attrs":{
"className":"text-nowrap"
},
"children":[
"(",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
{
"type":"table-link",
"target":"mk19_a_id_t24",
"wrapId":"1",
"children":[
"Table 24"
]
}
]
},
")"
]
},
"."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_a_id_t23",
"mk19_a_id_t24"
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"7c582e",
"children":[
"Risk factors for NTM infections include immunocompromise, chronic lung disease, and postoperative status."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d9665d",
"children":[
"NTM diagnosis is difficult because a positive culture result from a nonsterile site without evidence of disease may reflect colonization rather than infection. However, when recovered from a sterile site, active infection is likely. Because antibiotic susceptibility among species varies, it is important to identify organisms to species level. American Thoracic Society (ATS) guidelines (updated in 2020) recommend fulfillment of clinical, radiologic, and microbiologic criteria to diagnose an NTM pulmonary infection. Treatment is recommended for patients meeting diagnostic criteria, especially if acid-fast sputum smears are positive and/or cavitary lung disease is present. Most NTM infections require prolonged treatment with multiple antimicrobials; susceptibilities and ATS guidelines should be used to guide therapy."
]
},
{
"type":"keypoints",
"children":[
{
"type":"keypoint",
"hlId":"36138e",
"children":[
"Risk factors for nontuberculous mycobacteria infections include immunocompromise, chronic lung disease, and postoperative status; additionally, health care–associated ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium chimaera"
]
},
" infections have been associated with heater-cooler units used during cardiac surgery."
]
},
{
"type":"keypoint",
"hlId":"0afcc2",
"children":[
"Antibiotic susceptibility varies among species, so identifying nontuberculous mycobacterial organisms to a species level is important."
]
}
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_a_id_s7_1",
"title":{
"__html":"<i>Mycobacterium avium</i> Complex Infection"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"6be508",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium avium"
]
},
" Complex Infection"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0076db",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium avium"
]
},
" complex is a common cause of chronic lung infection worldwide. Cavitary lung disease is seen classically in middle-aged, or older adult men with underlying lung disease. Disseminated infection occurs predominantly in patients with HIV and CD4 cell counts less than 50/µL. The clinical presentation consists of fever, night sweats, weight loss, and gastrointestinal symptoms."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_a_id_s7_2",
"title":{
"__html":"<i>Mycobacterium kansasii</i>"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"c73bd2",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium kansasii"
]
},
" "
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"0fbbb1",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"M. kansasii"
]
},
" infection mimics pulmonary tuberculosis with cavitary lung disease. Predisposing conditions include underlying lung disease, alcoholism, and immunocompromised status."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_a_id_s7_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Rapidly Growing Mycobacteria"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"f391a1",
"children":[
"Rapidly Growing Mycobacteria"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f8764f",
"children":[
"Rapidly growing NTM have been implicated in NTM outbreaks. The most common rapidly growing mycobacterial species include ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"M. abscessus, M. chelonae"
]
},
", and ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"M. fortuitum"
]
},
"."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"f455ec",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"M. abscessus"
]
},
" is the most common. Considering its intrinsic drug resistance and increased prevalence, it is one of the most difficult to treat. Most of these mycobacteria are associated with chronic pulmonary infections and nonhealing ulcers unresponsive to appropriate antibiotic therapy."
]
},
{
"type":"keypoints",
"children":[
{
"type":"keypoint",
"hlId":"b48a23",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium avium"
]
},
" complex is a common cause of chronic lung infection worldwide, causing cavitary lung disease."
]
},
{
"type":"keypoint",
"hlId":"99f3e1",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium abscessus, Mycobacterium chelonae"
]
},
", and ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"i",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Mycobacterium fortuitum"
]
},
" can produce lung disease, adenitis, skin and soft tissue infections, surgical site infections, and catheter-related bloodstream infections."
]
}
]
}
]
},
